00:27:05,580 --> 00:27:06,580
 Let's follow these threads.

443
00:27:06,660 --> 00:27:11,160
 It could still be paralyzing for a certain percentage of them, you know, where they're like, I don't.

444
00:27:11,160 --> 00:27:21,040
 I get that, because I always felt, I mean, for me, I always felt like the versions of free writing that I encountered, I hated, like, if it's just sit down and generate, I'm like, I, what, where is that?

445
00:27:21,160 --> 00:27:21,500
 From where?

446
00:27:21,500 --> 00:27:28,020
 Whereas, for instance, if I, in the case of Derda or whatever, like, if I'm working with someone else's words, it's way easier, right?

447
00:27:28,020 --> 00:27:30,460
 Like, it's just like, okay, so here's a sentence.

448
00:27:30,840 --> 00:27:32,640
 I just literally transcribed the sentence.

449
00:27:32,780 --> 00:27:34,620
 Now, what the fuck does that sentence say, right?

450
00:27:34,780 --> 00:27:45,420
 Like, you know, I mean, really, and it's just way easier for me to, like, okay, I understand the project of trying to figure out what the hell he just said in that sentence and why he would say that and what implications it has.

451
00:27:45,580 --> 00:27:49,560
 That makes sense to me, as opposed to, oh, no, just right, like, why?

452
00:27:50,720 --> 00:27:52,500
 From what, with what, right?

453
00:27:52,620 --> 00:27:57,720
 And that risks so much, sort of, just like, I mean, emotivism or subjectivism.

454
00:27:57,980 --> 00:28:05,120
 And, you know, I imagine, like, certain versions of the bricolure, the fligneur, that's just sort of like a little bit of this and a little bit of that.

455
00:28:05,120 --> 00:28:08,820
 And then, you know, you just, you create a random series of associations.

456
00:28:09,140 --> 00:28:13,600
 And, yes, it will be inventive, but, like, it lacks rigor.

457
00:28:13,920 --> 00:28:19,740
 It lacks, it doesn't, like, you know, I mean, I think about the language of, like, the scene doesn't necessarily hold.

458
00:28:19,820 --> 00:28:25,500
 Just because you throw two things at each other doesn't mean that they stick without figuring out the particular places to stitch.

459
00:28:25,500 --> 00:28:35,500
 And, you know, I would just, I would say, like, I imagine, as Nate's working through the parts of the phenomenology, is that you're, like, you don't just randomly have it on, you know, this or that section.

460
00:28:35,820 --> 00:28:39,640
 It's like, you know, working through one part of it leads you to another part of it.

461
00:28:39,920 --> 00:28:45,500
 And, you know, like, and you don't pay attention to a certain part of it because, like, the threads don't stick, right?

462
00:28:45,500 --> 00:28:49,260
 But then you get to the part that does stick, and then you start, like, really carefully working through it.

463
00:28:49,600 --> 00:28:51,420
 And then that leads you to the next one.

464
00:28:51,720 --> 00:28:53,100
 And it kind of, like, the way that you've worked it.

465
00:28:53,920 --> 00:29:03,180
 And the truth is, you read it again in a year where you're working on a, you know, you're done with your dissertation, you're working on some other kind of essay, and you'd be like, oh, my God, how did I ignore all this religion stuff?

466
00:29:03,320 --> 00:29:06,300
 Like, this is so absolutely central to the whole thing, right?

467
00:29:07,180 --> 00:29:07,380
 Yeah.

468
00:29:07,960 --> 00:29:10,640
 But that is, like, this is how we should teach 18-year-olds.

469
00:29:10,760 --> 00:29:15,580
 But that, I mean, like, look, I don't teach thesis statements to my 18-year-olds, you know?

470
00:29:15,660 --> 00:29:23,220
 I mean, like, I do, though, like, I use the Bartholome book and, you know, the ways of reading, and, you know, it's like the, like, I teach Foucau and stuff like that.

471
00:29:23,340 --> 00:29:27,340
 And, you know, like, I do not begin hypotactically at all.

472
00:29:27,400 --> 00:29:31,840
 In fact, I kind of, like, give the argument maybe three or four weeks into it just as a quick aside.

473
00:29:31,980 --> 00:29:32,440
 I'm like, oh.

474
00:29:32,800 --> 00:29:42,720
 But, like, in a way that, like, that actually kind of makes sense now in a way that, like, if you were to give me that argument up front, it would have been just as much gibberish as everything else would have been gibberish.

475
00:29:43,240 --> 00:29:50,860
 And, you know, starting with is, like, like, I mean, the problem with the free riding is, like, how do you, you don't have, you don't know how to ride the bicycle yet.

476
00:29:51,000 --> 00:30:05,260
 So, it's slowing down, like, how do you take the sentence and then slow it down and problematize it or question it or, like, meditate on it for a little bit so that it can open itself up and lead you to another sentence or another passage.

477
00:30:05,260 --> 00:30:23,080
 And, like, just slowing down the movement of how to think one's way from passage to another passage to another passage is, like, I think both a really valuable way of learning to read but also an incredibly valuable way of learning to write as well.

478
00:30:23,200 --> 00:30:26,800
 Because it's the, for me, it's the writing on it that creates those, those linkages.

479
00:30:27,940 --> 00:30:33,220
 So, I mean, importantly, in that version, there are still sort of normative guardrails, right?

480
00:30:33,280 --> 00:30:44,360
 Like, it's not like, I mean, that's to me, and again, I also think that the version of free riding we're probably talking about is probably a dumb version of free, like, I believe that there's a more interesting version.

481
00:30:44,460 --> 00:30:45,200
 I just don't know it.

482
00:30:45,200 --> 00:30:49,580
 I mean, whatever, this is what I was told to do when I was 17 years old or something.

483
00:30:50,180 --> 00:30:55,220
 But, like, what, you know, what you're saying, it's, like, it's not about saying just do whatever feels right.

484
00:30:55,680 --> 00:30:57,060
 It's, like, it's not that.

485
00:30:57,220 --> 00:31:05,860
 It's, like, no, do a particular exercise, which is select something that interests you and figure out what it means and figure out its significance and figure out its relevance.

486
00:31:05,860 --> 00:31:10,340
 Like, in other words, it's solve a mystery kind of question.

487
00:31:10,680 --> 00:31:13,120
 And a mystery that you pick, which is, like, whatever.

488
00:31:13,320 --> 00:31:15,980
 Pick a sentence, pick a paragraph, pick whatever.

489
00:31:16,200 --> 00:31:18,460
 Like, something that has hooked you, that made you go, huh.

490
00:31:18,920 --> 00:31:20,920
 You know, and start there, right?

491
00:31:21,020 --> 00:31:21,660
 Like, that's just.

492
00:31:21,660 --> 00:31:23,680
 Well, I begin effectively, you know.

493
00:31:23,760 --> 00:31:25,340
 It's, like, all right, pick the thing.

494
00:31:25,660 --> 00:31:26,900
 You know, you don't have to pick the right thing.

495
00:31:26,980 --> 00:31:28,460
 There's not the right passage to begin with.

496
00:31:28,460 --> 00:31:28,640
 No, there's no right.

497
00:31:29,000 --> 00:31:29,180
 Right.

498
00:31:29,240 --> 00:31:36,240
 But choose the thing that irked you or confused you or frustrated you or intrigued you or sparked your curiosity.

499
00:31:36,440 --> 00:31:40,720
 Whatever it is, like, whatever that emotive reason is, like, up, like, in a sentence or two.

500
00:31:40,720 --> 00:31:46,480
 Like, this intrigued me or irked me because, and then here's a particular thing about it that did this.

501
00:31:46,960 --> 00:31:51,360
 And here's how I'm going to try to, like, think through what about it is doing this thing.

502
00:31:51,600 --> 00:31:55,660
 And then once you have that machinery running, it takes you to another passage.

503
00:31:56,180 --> 00:31:58,320
 And then you don't need the emotive thing anymore.

504
00:31:58,460 --> 00:32:05,840
 Because the first line is opening up the second passage, which opens up the third, which opens up the fourth, as long as you do the work of the connecting.

505
00:32:06,460 --> 00:32:09,420
 And that, to me, is also an infinitely generative machine.

506
00:32:09,620 --> 00:32:14,580
 You know, like, I say you could literally follow this process and write forever.

507
00:32:15,460 --> 00:32:18,720
 But I'm asking you to do it in, you know, 800 words.

508
00:32:18,800 --> 00:32:21,820
 So stop at 800 words, right, whatever cycle you head to.

509
00:32:22,580 --> 00:32:36,680
 I mean, it's funny because, I mean, honestly, like, when I undertook to teach this class, I limited, just because Derrida is so massive, I limited it to Derrida on writing as the sort of thematic, you know, focal point.

510
00:32:36,680 --> 00:32:43,900
 But I always thought it was going to be, like, just a philosophy class on Derrida on writing that, of course, had theory implications for the field of composition studies.

511
00:32:44,580 --> 00:32:52,040
 But what has actually become, it is a lot of that, but what it has also become is a fucking graduate level composition class, right?

512
00:32:52,080 --> 00:32:56,220
 Like, it really, like, and a pedagogy class for me of, like, well, let's try this.

513
00:32:56,320 --> 00:33:02,600
 Let's see, like, for next week, you know, let's all do this sort of writing experiment and see what happens.

514
00:33:02,660 --> 00:33:03,900
 And for the week after, we'll do that.

515
00:33:03,900 --> 00:33:14,160
 It's really become a composition class without, you know, we are, I am acting as a writing instructor in the most conventional sense.

516
00:33:14,160 --> 00:33:19,340
 Now, what we're writing about is Derrida, so it's very specific and located.

517
00:33:19,620 --> 00:33:24,060
 But, like, man, it's just, I didn't expect that to be the case at all.

518
00:33:24,200 --> 00:33:26,020
 And yet, it has happened that way.

519
00:33:26,500 --> 00:33:26,640
 Yeah.

520
00:33:26,860 --> 00:33:27,100
 Yeah.

521
00:33:27,460 --> 00:33:28,020
 That's cool.

522
00:33:28,640 --> 00:33:43,280
 Yeah, I mean, I feel like also, like, in terms of getting over the hump where writing becomes enjoyable, which I think is sometimes the wall for even graduate students, where it's seen as this task that they have to do, right?

523
00:33:43,280 --> 00:33:46,620
 Even if it's the thing that they want to have their career be based on.

524
00:33:46,740 --> 00:33:58,320
 Like, it's anxiety-inducing and it's seen as they still sort of inherit all that traditional stuff where you're supposed to exhibit mastery, etc.

525
00:33:58,520 --> 00:34:07,180
 Like, to think of writing or to be able to do it as a creative process, I think is a real challenge for a lot of students.

526
00:34:07,340 --> 00:34:17,040
 And I, but I do, I really love the metaphor of, like, sampling and trying to employ that as a kind of method or orientation.

527
00:34:17,040 --> 00:34:21,360
 Because I do that in a bunch of different milieus.

528
00:34:21,560 --> 00:34:26,760
 Like, with music, obviously, sampling, that would be the term where it's most typically employed.

529
00:34:26,920 --> 00:34:37,860
 Where you take something, like, a sample from an old 70s hit or something obscure and you put it into another context and you make it function differently.

530
00:34:38,200 --> 00:34:41,260
 You put it under a hip-hop beat or something, right?

531
00:34:41,420 --> 00:34:46,500
 So you transport it into maybe a current context and reformulate it that way.

532
00:34:46,500 --> 00:34:51,080
 And you can do the exact same thing with Foucault or Hegel or whoever.

533
00:34:51,540 --> 00:35:00,700
 So you can, like, key into disciplinary power and see how, why is that still relevant for the university context, for society writ large, you know?

534
00:35:00,760 --> 00:35:03,540
 So you can do that kind of creative work.

535
00:35:04,260 --> 00:35:08,640
 It's just, it's difficult to get into that disposition, I feel like, for...

536
00:35:08,640 --> 00:35:14,460
 So this is, like, the hinge on which I, like, I'm sometimes I'm, like, totally with it and then sometimes I'm, like, eh.

537
00:35:14,920 --> 00:35:19,340
 And when you were describing it on the musical side, I was totally with it.

538
00:35:19,440 --> 00:35:24,480
 Because, I mean, because it's, like, you take the sample and then you put it in a new context.

539
00:35:24,680 --> 00:35:26,800
 And then, as you said, you have to make it, right?

540
00:35:26,880 --> 00:35:32,060
 You have to remake it within that context and remake the context around it.

541
00:35:32,060 --> 00:35:36,160
 You have to allow it to sort of, like, do its difference to the thing, right?

542
00:35:36,460 --> 00:35:36,620
 Right.

543
00:35:36,640 --> 00:35:50,520
 And that's, like, and I think you could do the same thing with, you know, inserting part of Foucault into something else and then treat Foucault as a kind of antigen that starts working through the new body that you've placed it into.

544
00:35:50,980 --> 00:36:03,560
 But it was just, like, and I don't think this is what you were getting after, but part of the imagery that you were using was more, like, how is Foucault still relevant to, you know, the university, you know, education complex?

545
00:36:03,900 --> 00:36:19,760
 And just that language made me think more of that transcendental relationship was, like, I will take Foucault as a lens and then this coherent thing called Foucault will, you know, provide a particular window or vision of the university lens, right?

546
00:36:19,760 --> 00:36:36,700
 Which, again, is going to introduce, like, the problems of masteries, like, how do I contain Foucault, turn it into a lens, be able to then methodologically use it to reveal this thing called the university, which, you know, what am I going to create the boundaries on, what am I going to focus on?

547
00:36:36,700 --> 00:36:41,740
 But you used to start, like, but I like the language of sampling more there.

548
00:36:41,820 --> 00:36:55,020
 Like, how do I take, slice out this, like, think about it more biological, slice out this, like, do a biopsy of Foucault, insert it in this new body, and then allow it to start to live in this new body and then see what it starts to do.

549
00:36:55,920 --> 00:37:04,960
 So one of the things this makes me think of is that what my undergrad sci-fi, which I told you is a non-majors class, and it's kind of a blow-off class, right?

550
00:37:04,960 --> 00:37:07,440
 It's just sort of, like, we watch movies and talk about them.

551
00:37:08,340 --> 00:37:17,940
 But the times when it works the best, and I've tried, I mean, I've tried to formalize it a little bit, but, like, it's not like you have to have an understanding of the movie that we watched.

552
00:37:18,120 --> 00:37:24,620
 Like, pick a fucking scene that you thought something interesting happened in, and then connect it in some way, like, why do you think it's interesting?

553
00:37:24,800 --> 00:37:30,340
 Like, oh, because that's a lot like circumstances today that are, and that's, it's the same kind of move.

554
00:37:30,340 --> 00:37:38,300
 Like, you're just, say, you're hooking into a moment without necessarily any kind of global understanding of the plot, the characters, and all that sort of shit.

555
00:37:38,560 --> 00:37:45,540
 Hooking into a moment and then connecting it to whether it's a situation in your life or in popular culture or whatever else.

556
00:37:45,900 --> 00:37:55,100
 And it's so generative, like, they, they, when you can get them to do that, and to, if you can get them to sort of say, I'm not asking you to make an argument about the matrix.

557
00:37:55,260 --> 00:37:59,260
 I'm not asking you to form some judgment or to do a reading of the matrix.

558
00:37:59,520 --> 00:38:07,780
 I'm asking you to, like, find a moment in the matrix that hooks you for, oftentimes, for reasons, like, I don't really know, but that seemed really cool.

559
00:38:07,940 --> 00:38:09,420
 So, like, I want to think about that.

560
00:38:09,480 --> 00:38:13,100
 And then we start talking about it, and they're like, oh, that reminds me of this other thing.

561
00:38:13,180 --> 00:38:15,580
 And it's the same kind of, now, that's video, right?

562
00:38:15,600 --> 00:38:16,160
 That's movies.

563
00:38:16,340 --> 00:38:20,160
 It doesn't have, and I say that partly because it doesn't have to be Derrida, right?

564
00:38:20,200 --> 00:38:28,580
 It's just sort of, so there's a different way of approaching even movies, which is, hypotactically, like, what is your, what is your thesis about the matrix, right?

565
00:38:28,580 --> 00:38:33,660
 Like, and that's, that is the thing that I feel like they find debilitating, because they're like, I don't know.

566
00:38:33,720 --> 00:38:34,480
 I don't know what to think.

567
00:38:34,540 --> 00:38:35,760
 That's a big, that's a lot of stuff.

568
00:38:35,820 --> 00:38:36,700
 I don't really, whatever.

569
00:38:36,820 --> 00:38:37,800
 It was boring, you know?

570
00:38:38,740 --> 00:38:39,780
 But if you, if you.

571
00:38:39,940 --> 00:38:40,900
 Nobody says that about the matrix.

572
00:38:41,940 --> 00:38:43,640
 But if you limit it, right?

573
00:38:43,680 --> 00:38:47,420
 If you say, like, look, you don't have to have an opinion or something about the matrix.

574
00:38:47,420 --> 00:38:50,520
 Just, like, what was something in the movie that made you go, like, huh?

575
00:38:51,060 --> 00:38:52,740
 Or, like, eh, whatever.

576
00:38:52,920 --> 00:38:56,820
 Like, to have some kind of response to, and then let's play out.

577
00:38:56,840 --> 00:38:57,540
 And talk it through.

578
00:38:57,540 --> 00:38:57,960
 What was that?

579
00:38:57,960 --> 00:39:02,800
 Yeah, and then, and it creates, and I'm like, you know, that's critical thinking.

580
00:39:02,900 --> 00:39:10,660
 Like, what we just did was we used whatever the text was, the matrix, whatever, to sort of think about whatever else.

581
00:39:10,660 --> 00:39:11,940
 Like, the Will Smith slap.

582
00:39:12,160 --> 00:39:12,440
 It's a catalyst.

583
00:39:12,440 --> 00:39:13,600
 Yeah, it doesn't, it doesn't matter.

584
00:39:14,280 --> 00:39:14,980
 Yeah, yeah.

585
00:39:15,220 --> 00:39:15,880
 Well, I mean.

586
00:39:16,040 --> 00:39:19,660
 But speaking of, speaking of the Will Smith slap, like, I mean, I just, I just threw that out there.

587
00:39:19,660 --> 00:39:20,640
 But, like, that was one of the things.

588
00:39:20,980 --> 00:39:28,440
 I had this, I had a, I hope it's going to turn into, like, a watershed life moment for me in response to that.

589
00:39:29,440 --> 00:39:32,540
 Insofar as I got, I mean, I didn't watch it and didn't know about it.

590
00:39:32,560 --> 00:39:34,380
 And I got my, like, sort of news updates.

591
00:39:34,520 --> 00:39:38,080
 And then the next day I went on social media and, like, everyone had opinions.

592
00:39:38,080 --> 00:39:38,920
 So what was it?

593
00:39:39,020 --> 00:39:41,420
 Will Smith slapped Chris Rock?

594
00:39:41,440 --> 00:39:42,980
 Slapped Chris Rock at the Oscars, yeah.

595
00:39:43,060 --> 00:39:46,600
 Like, as a, like, staged thing?

596
00:39:46,620 --> 00:39:46,900
 No.

597
00:39:47,280 --> 00:39:49,340
 Well, but that's one of the, that's one of the questions.

598
00:39:49,840 --> 00:39:50,720
 It doesn't seem like it.

599
00:39:51,360 --> 00:39:51,940
 But whatever.

600
00:39:52,220 --> 00:39:52,340
 Like, everybody had.

601
00:39:52,340 --> 00:39:53,980
 Like, did Chris Rock seem pissed about it?

602
00:39:54,640 --> 00:39:58,080
 But, like, hold on, let me get to, just shut up.

603
00:39:58,080 --> 00:39:58,280
 Okay, I'm sorry.

604
00:39:58,460 --> 00:39:58,960
 Yeah, yeah, yeah.

605
00:39:58,960 --> 00:39:59,640
 Let me get to the fucking point.

606
00:40:00,640 --> 00:40:05,660
 The point was, you, yes, I get that you are in fucking Canada, so they don't have popular culture there.

607
00:40:05,760 --> 00:40:09,980
 But everyone I knew in the States, like, had opinions, right?

608
00:40:09,980 --> 00:40:14,880
 And all the opinions, what the opinions were, were, like, different ways of contextualizing it.

609
00:40:14,940 --> 00:40:16,340
 Which is, it's an issue of race.

610
00:40:16,540 --> 00:40:17,700
 It's an issue of masculinity.

611
00:40:18,080 --> 00:40:20,600
 It's an issue of mental illness.

612
00:40:20,880 --> 00:40:25,220
 It's an issue, like, it's an issue of stage versus, you know, artifice versus reality.

613
00:40:25,360 --> 00:40:29,240
 Like, so there were all these different contextualizations which were vying for.

614
00:40:29,340 --> 00:40:31,160
 Because we all agreed on the act, right?

615
00:40:31,180 --> 00:40:32,880
 Like, the text was, like, there.

616
00:40:33,080 --> 00:40:36,920
 And so you just had all of these different people contextualizing in different ways

617
00:40:36,920 --> 00:40:40,620
 and having sort of strong opinions about their way of contextualizing it.

618
00:40:40,940 --> 00:40:44,060
 And for whatever reason, I mean, I read through a lot of these things.

619
00:40:44,060 --> 00:40:46,560
 And I was just like, I have no opinion about this.

620
00:40:46,560 --> 00:40:48,940
 Like, and not because I think it's unimportant.

621
00:40:49,160 --> 00:40:50,580
 That would be an opinion, right?

622
00:40:50,820 --> 00:40:53,540
 Like, or I was just like, I have no opinion.

623
00:40:53,540 --> 00:40:55,140
 And my God, I don't need to.

624
00:40:55,260 --> 00:41:00,260
 It was this glorious moment where, for the first time, I was like, I don't have to have an opinion about this.

625
00:41:00,320 --> 00:41:08,600
 I don't have to try to come up with some pithy new angle that the other people haven't had or a way of summing up, like, the underlying logic of people's angles.

626
00:41:08,780 --> 00:41:10,260
 I was like, I see what's going on.

627
00:41:10,600 --> 00:41:17,780
 Like, I feel like I get what's going on, which is different attempts to contextualize, all of which are claiming that theirs is the right way, right?

628
00:41:17,880 --> 00:41:20,440
 And I don't have an investment.

629
00:41:20,580 --> 00:41:22,080
 I don't disinvest either.

630
00:41:22,200 --> 00:41:23,880
 I don't think it's a foolish thing to do.

631
00:41:24,100 --> 00:41:25,060
 I don't think it's stupid.

